WEBVTT

00:02.900 --> 00:19.822
A black delegate was going to be coming from to the 
campus and how would the campus react and how could

00:02.900 --> 00:19.822
we prepare for this and so of course all of us on the 
executive committee were in favor of it.

00:25.729 --> 00:30.055
We did not want to publicize it however because We 
didn't want to give any, if there were any

00:30.710 --> 00:46.754
rednecks, we didn't want to give lead time for any 
opposition to form and to create problems or

00:30.710 --> 00:46.754
demonstrations or anything that might bring bad 
attention to A&M. So

00:47.595 --> 00:53.043
we decided we wouldn't publicize it. Nobody would 
say anything other than to make arrangements

00:53.083 --> 00:59.653
behind the scenes.

01:00.325 --> 01:11.479
And I think they had made arrangements for him to 
stay with, I think Wayne or somebody that Wayne

01:00.325 --> 01:11.479
knew had made arrangements for him to stay with 
maybe the black minister in the community. And

01:13.762 --> 01:18.648
then later decided to put him in at the MSC. And it 
all worked out okay. And it all worked out okay.

01:21.772 --> 01:25.337
Well, it did except that on the first day, When all 
the delegates began to arrive and they realized

01:26.330 --> 01:37.622
there was a black delegate there, some of the 
delegates who were our guests wanted to make a real

01:26.330 --> 01:37.622
big deal of it. They wanted to focus on him as if he 
were a celebrity rather than focus on the topic of

01:37.662 --> 01:44.069
SCONA. And we said, no, we don't want to do that. 
Everything's going to be normal. You're not going

01:49.174 --> 01:52.978
to make him a cause celebre. focus on this. And we 
had to do almost some arm twisting and almost

01:55.753 --> 02:07.405
threatened to send some of them home as being 
ungracious guests if they didn't settle down. And

02:07.746 --> 02:17.777
I remember having to talk to some of the delegates 
that wanted to do that, to publicize this, and

02:07.746 --> 02:17.777
telling them, look, we want to set a precedent. We 
want it to go well. We don't want to give an

02:18.838 --> 02:21.801
opposition chance to form. We wanted to do it, 
treat everything as if it's normal, and we'll

02:22.372 --> 02:28.299
publicize it after the fact. You can still get all 
the mileage that you want out of it, but without

02:29.060 --> 02:34.146
creating a big incident. And finally, we 
convinced them, the cooler heads prevail, to not

02:34.166 --> 02:41.235
make this a big thing, and it went well. It was a 
precedent-setting move. What about one or two of

02:44.318 --> 02:47.502
the highlights, the high points? That one ended up 
positively, but some other things that you

02:48.190 --> 02:54.124
remember being very proud of in your Scona 
leadership years? We initiated

02:55.908 --> 03:07.093
what we called at the time cultural leadership 
activities. Wayne and one of his assistants named

03:07.597 --> 03:12.223
Bill Height and I went down to Houston. We met with 
John Lindsay, we met with Nina Vance at the Alley

03:12.263 --> 03:27.782
Theater, we met with a number of folks, the 
director of the Houston Symphony Orchestra, I

03:12.263 --> 03:27.782
don't remember that name right now, but What we 
wanted to do was to have a cultural weekend with

03:29.078 --> 03:43.740
selected student leaders on campus being invited 
to go by invitation, not by volunteer group,

03:29.078 --> 03:43.740
because we knew it had to be, especially 
initially, had to be a small control group. And we

03:45.382 --> 03:47.566
did that in Houston, and that one went well. So the 
next year, we did one in Dallas, including the, we

03:47.606 --> 03:57.921
timed it for the opera, Dallas opera season. and uh 
and that kicked off it took hold and it's been going

03:58.323 --> 04:25.630
ever since and it's now called spring leadership 
it has it has evolved some in selection criteria

03:58.323 --> 04:25.630
and what they do and where they go but basically 
that was initiated in 60 61

03:58.323 --> 04:25.630
or 62. the second one was the msc travel committee

04:27.601 --> 04:31.812
And this was one of Wayne's brainstorms. He 
probably got the idea from some of his association

04:32.874 --> 04:43.922
conferences with other student union leaders, 
but the idea was to publicize and attract and

04:44.527 --> 05:00.325
motivate students to want to go any kind of an 
overseas experience so we got a lot of literature

04:44.527 --> 05:00.325
on things like the experiment international 
living uh... this operation crossroads and any

05:00.305 --> 05:07.273
other kinds of activities that would facilitate 
and just publicize opportunities. And then the

05:07.333 --> 05:12.500
students, of course, would have to volunteer and 
sometimes raise money and pay for them

05:07.333 --> 05:12.500
themselves. But it was a great experience. Well, 
that first year, I got caught up with the publicity

05:14.182 --> 05:18.607
and what we're doing. That's when I signed up for 
that Operation Crossroads to East Africa.

05:25.904 --> 05:41.445
Reggie Richardson, who was the deputy corps 
commander, was the first chairman of the Travel

05:25.904 --> 05:41.445
Committee and he got all the information, all the 
publicity together and helped facilitate this.

05:41.505 --> 05:47.794
We had four people, two of us went on Operation 
Crossroads and two to experiment international

05:41.505 --> 05:47.794
living. And then the next year, there were several 
more. And then my brother, who came in as a freshman

05:53.210 --> 06:01.702
the year I graduated, we overlapped there in the 
fall of 63.

06:04.907 --> 06:10.134
But he eventually became active in the MSC. And I 
think he was a travel committee chairman. And he

06:12.598 --> 06:16.363
went to Switzerland with the experiment in 
international living. as a result of that. So he

06:18.688 --> 06:22.835
was also in Hellcat 9. Do you realize now in looking 
